Hi. Welcome to Surf's Up.
Audio commentary.

2
00:00:06,473 --> 00:00:07,673
I will be your guide...

3
00:00:08,007 --> 00:00:09,937
.. through this wonderful presentation
of Surf's Up.

4
00:00:10,377 --> 00:00:12,457
I'm Chris Buck, one of the directors.

5
00:00:12,913 --> 00:00:14,613
Ash Brannon, another director.

6
00:00:15,015 --> 00:00:18,495
And I'm Chris Jenkins
and I make the coffee.

7
00:00:19,152 --> 00:00:20,932
And it's good coffee too.

8
00:00:21,355 --> 00:00:22,255
Not that crystal stuff.

9
00:00:22,556 --> 00:00:24,606
And he's the producer, okay,
here we go.

10
00:00:25,058 --> 00:00:27,168
Hey, look at that logo, guys.

11
00:00:27,628 --> 00:00:30,758
We came up with the logo
just for Surf's Up.

12
00:00:32,766 --> 00:00:34,025
Here we are.

13
00:00:34,368 --> 00:00:35,238
Okay.

14
00:00:35,536 --> 00:00:37,026
Interesting thing about this one
was that...

15
00:00:37,404 --> 00:00:41,384
.. this was the last scene created
and the first scene in the movie.

16
00:00:42,276 --> 00:00:45,316
But the movie originally started
with the sequences coming up...

17
00:00:45,913 --> 00:00:48,602
.. which was what we call
the legend sequence, right?

18
00:00:49,149 --> 00:00:52,339
And, Ash, you boarded the whole bit--
The sort of history of surfing.

19
00:00:52,953 --> 00:00:54,733
-Yeah.
-We thought that we needed Cody.

20
00:00:55,155 --> 00:00:57,555
Cody to introduce it and get to know
Cody a little bit more before--

21
00:00:58,058 --> 00:00:59,668
Yeah, it was originally
a disembodied voice.

22
00:01:00,060 --> 00:01:01,840
You didn't know who it was.

23
00:01:03,630 --> 00:01:06,030
Okay, everybody wants to know...

24
00:01:06,533 --> 00:01:09,963
.. why a documentary, right, guys?

25
00:01:10,604 --> 00:01:11,804
Why do an animated documentary?

26
00:01:12,573 --> 00:01:13,592
Lots of reasons.

27
00:01:13,907 --> 00:01:16,657
First of all, surf videos are actually
made that way.

28
00:01:17,210 --> 00:01:18,440
And we thought it would be cool...

29
00:01:18,779 --> 00:01:21,939
..to do the subject of Surf's Up
as a surf documentary.

30
00:01:22,549 --> 00:01:24,509
Well, there was originally
a storyline, right?

31
00:01:24,952 --> 00:01:27,442
When Chris Jenkins was on this
about four and a half years ago.

32
00:01:27,955 --> 00:01:29,945
It was 48 years ago, actually.

33
00:01:30,390 --> 00:01:33,260
It was a comedy based
on Romeo and Juliet.

34
00:01:34,094 --> 00:01:36,753
Yes, it was, Ash Brannon.
Thank you.

35
00:01:37,297 --> 00:01:38,467
And they were racing cars...

36
00:01:38,799 --> 00:01:40,609
..and they were wearing clothes
and all that, right?

37
00:01:41,034 --> 00:01:42,494
Yeah, and they were dressed
as policemen...

38
00:01:42,869 --> 00:01:45,589
..and they were falling off cliffs
and dying and--

39
00:01:46,139 --> 00:01:47,749
-Isn't really a comedy.
-Okay.

40
00:01:48,141 --> 00:01:51,621
-And how did it become this, Chris?
-It became this--

41
00:01:52,279 --> 00:01:53,949
It became this when, you know...

42
00:01:54,348 --> 00:01:56,928
. I'm kind of looking at the idea
of doing a surf movie.

43
00:01:57,451 --> 00:02:01,791
And looking at the prevalence
for surf docs...

44
00:02:02,556 --> 00:02:03,986
.. movies to be done
as documentaries.

45
00:02:04,358 --> 00:02:09,958
Or for the whole reality TV thing
to be realized in animation.

46
00:02:10,896 --> 00:02:13,887
-Did that make sense?
-Yeah, kind of. In a Welsh kind of way.

47
00:02:17,838 --> 00:02:20,118
And the storyline was designed
to work as a documentary.

48
00:02:20,607 --> 00:02:24,007
We had to imagine that there was a kid
we heard about who's up and coming.

49
00:02:24,645 --> 00:02:26,575
We decided to send a crew
down there and follow him...

50
00:02:27,014 --> 00:02:28,414
..as he went to his first contest.

51
00:02:28,782 --> 00:02:29,892
And then follow him.

52
00:02:30,217 --> 00:02:31,917
Yeah, and be able to just put
a camera--

53
00:02:32,319 --> 00:02:34,249
Not a camera. What do they call
the things where you--?

54
00:02:34,688 --> 00:02:36,118
-Like a microphone.
-Microphone, yeah.

55
00:02:36,490 --> 00:02:38,040
Like that thing in front of you
right now.

56
00:02:38,425 --> 00:02:39,595
But it's interesting, we had rules.

57
00:02:39,926 --> 00:02:43,386
Like, we never saw
the documentarians. We never--

58
00:02:44,031 --> 00:02:46,841
No, people really wanted to know
who the documentarians are.

59
00:02:47,401 --> 00:02:48,661
-What species.
-Yeah.

60
00:02:49,002 --> 00:02:50,312
And we felt that if we did that...

61
00:02:50,671 --> 00:02:53,831
.. then we would really be winking
at the audience...

62
00:02:54,441 --> 00:02:55,871
..in a particular way, you know?

63
00:02:56,243 --> 00:02:57,263
It would be more--

64
00:02:57,577 --> 00:02:59,537
I suppose, more mockumentary
in that way...

65
00:02:59,980 --> 00:03:01,290
.. than we wanted it to be.

66
00:03:01,648 --> 00:03:03,787
And the thing, I think,
that fascinated me was that...

67
00:03:04,251 --> 00:03:07,501
..we could get inside
an animated character's head.

68
00:03:08,121 --> 00:03:11,021
Via the interviews, you can find out
what these guys were thinking...

69
00:03:11,591 --> 00:03:15,491
..and what they just thought
about the scene that we just shot.

70
00:03:16,196 --> 00:03:18,246
I don't know. It's something
that we'd never done before...

71
00:03:18,699 --> 00:03:19,659
..in other animated movies.

72
00:03:19,966 --> 00:03:23,626
There was a lot of things going on,
the idea that in this day and age...

73
00:03:24,304 --> 00:03:27,234
.. everybody seems to have an opinion
or reaction to a camera...

74
00:03:27,808 --> 00:03:30,738
.. being put in their face and they have
an opinion about something.

75
00:03:31,311 --> 00:03:32,331
Maybe they're hiding things.

76
00:03:32,646 --> 00:03:35,546
Maybe they wanna use it
as a confessional.

77
00:03:36,116 --> 00:03:41,116
And it just felt it was the right time
to take an animated feature...

78
00:03:41,421 --> 00:03:41,851
And it just felt it was the right time
to take an animated feature...

79
00:03:42,089 --> 00:03:45,749
..and really follow the inner life
of these characters on the screen.

80
00:03:46,426 --> 00:03:49,766
Well, people are fascinated
by the documentary and reality TV.

81
00:03:50,397 --> 00:03:51,930
I mean, I know that's what we watch
at home.

82
00:03:51,932 --> 00:03:52,101
I mean, I know that's what we watch
at home.

83
00:03:52,299 --> 00:03:53,789
There's so many of those shows
who love it.

84
00:03:54,167 --> 00:03:55,867
I mean, a lot of times, it's what,
you know...

85
00:03:56,269 --> 00:03:58,819
.Jit's what the camera catches
that they weren't supposed to catch...

86
00:03:59,339 --> 00:04:00,209
.. that everybody loves.

87
00:04:00,507 --> 00:04:02,677
Or the thing that somebody
said that, you know...

88
00:04:03,143 --> 00:04:05,633
.. they didn't really mean to say this
or whatever...

89
00:04:06,146 --> 00:04:08,076
...but it's very telling.

90
00:04:09,483 --> 00:04:11,383
The-camera-doesn't-lie
kind of thing, so....

91
00:04:11,818 --> 00:04:14,778
-We planned in a kind of spontaneity.
-It's fun.

92
00:04:15,355 --> 00:04:16,224
Planned spontaneity.

93
00:04:16,523 --> 00:04:19,153
Planned these things, like the camera
would stay on a character...

94
00:04:19,692 --> 00:04:21,743
.. after they'd finished saying
what they were gonna say.

95
00:04:22,195 --> 00:04:25,235
And their reaction, then,
after their last sentence...

96
00:04:25,832 --> 00:04:29,522
..Was more telling
than what they were trained to tell you.

97
00:04:30,604 --> 00:04:33,704
And it wasn't easy
the whole way through.

98
00:04:34,307 --> 00:04:36,707
There are a lot of rules we set up
for ourselves.

99
00:04:37,210 --> 00:04:38,760
And it was tough
between the camera work...

100
00:04:39,146 --> 00:04:40,166
.. where the camera could be.

101
00:04:40,480 --> 00:04:43,110
The type of questions
that we would ask these guys.

102
00:04:43,650 --> 00:04:46,719
When the character's
aware of the camera or not.

103
00:04:47,487 --> 00:04:48,947
These are rules,
set of rules that we had.

104
00:04:49,322 --> 00:04:50,612
Once in a while, we'd break them.

105
00:04:50,957 --> 00:04:54,177
And we can talk about those
as we go through this but....

106
00:04:55,162 --> 00:04:57,152
It's kind of
the whole documentary thing.

107
00:04:57,597 --> 00:04:59,436
Remember, we had lots of talk about,
you know...

108
00:04:59,866 --> 00:05:01,265
.. where the camera crew
is coming from...

109
00:05:01,635 --> 00:05:02,715
..and how did they get there.

110
00:05:03,036 --> 00:05:05,146
All the kinds of things
that quite honestly in the end--

111
00:05:05,605 --> 00:05:07,625
-Nobody thinks about.
-Yeah.

112
00:05:08,074 --> 00:05:10,184
He can't help it.
That's just the way he is.

113
00:05:11,711 --> 00:05:13,671
It was important
when we started the movie...

114
00:05:14,114 --> 00:05:16,513
...we knew it was a surf movie,
but the surfing is really a metaphor.

115
00:05:17,017 --> 00:05:19,417
And we didn't want the film just to be
about surfing per se.

116
00:05:19,920 --> 00:05:21,700
And we came across an article...

117
00:05:22,122 --> 00:05:23,852
.. by some guys named
the Malloy brothers.

118
00:05:24,257 --> 00:05:25,367
They said something interesting.

119
00:05:25,692 --> 00:05:27,682
They said, "A lot of surf movies
don't get it right.

120
00:05:28,128 --> 00:05:29,967
They think it's all about just riding
the waves.

121
00:05:30,397 --> 00:05:32,296
And it's really about life
and the way you live it."

122
00:05:32,732 --> 00:05:35,922
And we just really fell in love
with that concept.

123
00:05:36,536 --> 00:05:37,846
Being one with the wave
and with life--

124
00:05:38,205 --> 00:05:40,604
And that's how we, you know,
faced the production every day.

125
00:05:41,541 --> 00:05:43,820
We came in
to have a good time every day.

126
00:05:45,011 --> 00:05:46,321
-Not gonna touch you.
-Do you see this?

127
00:05:46,680 --> 00:05:47,760
-Don't. Please?
-I'm not.

128
00:05:48,081 --> 00:05:49,041
Well, now, Shiverpool's...

129
00:05:49,349 --> 00:05:51,599
.. kind of inspired
by an Errol Morris film...

130
00:05:52,085 --> 00:05:53,895
..he did one about a
town in Florida...

131
00:05:54,321 --> 00:05:56,601
.. where nothing happens.

132
00:05:57,090 --> 00:05:59,049
This is where, again,
we play with-- This whole sequence...

133
00:05:59,492 --> 00:06:00,952
..we play with the whole
documentary feel.

134
00:06:01,328 --> 00:06:03,758
Like you're saying,
that's an Errol Morris film.

135
00:06:04,264 --> 00:06:06,574
The cutting that we did,
we kept moving things around.

136
00:06:07,067 --> 00:06:07,967
And then the interviews.

137
00:06:09,870 --> 00:06:11,003
Yeah, our editor Ivan Bilancio
kind of took all these moments...

138
00:06:11,004 --> 00:06:13,224
Yeah, our editor Ivan Bilancio
kind of took all these moments...

139
00:06:13,707 --> 00:06:14,727
..as if he had coverage.

140
00:06:15,842 --> 00:06:17,712
And just found an entertaining way
to intercut them.

141
00:06:18,144 --> 00:06:20,954
Kind of a proof of concept,
this whole sequence, in a way.

142
00:06:21,514 --> 00:06:23,824
Right, ! remember this is one
of the first ones.

143
00:06:24,584 --> 00:06:26,194
And it was really interesting how...

144
00:06:26,586 --> 00:06:28,486
..when Errol came in
to take a look at the stuff...

145
00:06:28,922 --> 00:06:30,702
..and we were calling it
a mockumentary...

146
00:06:31,124 --> 00:06:33,584
..he said, "It's not a mockumentary.
It's a documentary."

147
00:06:34,094 --> 00:06:35,994
-Right.
-Because we don't nod to the camera.

148
00:06:36,429 --> 00:06:37,299
Right.

149
00:06:37,597 --> 00:06:40,087
Yeah, that was important to us,
to keep the tongue out of the cheek.

150
00:06:40,600 --> 00:06:42,300
And have these characters believe
who they were.

151
00:06:42,702 --> 00:06:44,542
And you get the humor
out of the seriousness of that.

152
00:06:44,971 --> 00:06:46,021
Right.

153
00:06:46,773 --> 00:06:50,493
But this kind of performance too,
all this improv...

154
00:06:51,177 --> 00:06:55,837
..all these multiple cast recording,
this was pretty new.

155
00:06:56,650 --> 00:06:57,940
I mean, it sounds strange to say it...

156
00:06:58,285 --> 00:07:00,475
.. but this was a new technique
for animation.

157
00:07:00,954 --> 00:07:01,974
Because in animated movies...

158
00:07:02,289 --> 00:07:04,339
.. usually we have the actors
by themselves.

159
00:07:04,791 --> 00:07:06,101
And we get a very clean recording...

160
00:07:06,459 --> 00:07:08,209
..and then you can cut
everybody together.

161
00:07:08,628 --> 00:07:10,298
The problem with that is that,
you get a very--

162
00:07:10,697 --> 00:07:12,477
You can get
a very sterile performance.

163
00:07:12,899 --> 00:07:15,939
And they don't always feel like
they're in the same room together.

164
00:07:16,536 --> 00:07:18,706
Or that they're actually relating
to the other character.

165
00:07:19,439 --> 00:07:20,669
Biggest challenge for an editor...

166
00:07:21,007 --> 00:07:25,257
.. 1s to cut a natural performance
from a bunch of different sessions.

167
00:07:26,012 --> 00:07:28,382
And they said, "Well, let's skip
all that. Let's encourage--

168
00:07:28,882 --> 00:07:30,782
Get them in together,
have them overlap...

169
00:07:31,217 --> 00:07:34,027
.. have them, you know, of course,
work off the script...

170
00:07:34,587 --> 00:07:37,046
..but turn the pages over and see...

171
00:07:37,557 --> 00:07:40,427
.. and just let it, kind of,
go on its own and wing it."

172
00:07:40,994 --> 00:07:43,544
We told all the actors
we're gonna do this at the outset.

173
00:07:44,064 --> 00:07:45,354
-And they were all excited.
-Right.

174
00:07:45,699 --> 00:07:47,069
And they were all really good at it.

175
00:07:47,434 --> 00:07:52,094
Not all actors can pull that off.

176
00:07:53,239 --> 00:07:55,258
James Woods, of course.

177
00:07:55,942 --> 00:07:57,722
We have so much recording
of James...

178
00:07:58,545 --> 00:08:01,945
... that in the end, we were
unable to use for all sorts of reasons.

179
00:08:02,582 --> 00:08:05,861
It was a heart thing, you know?
Can we just take five minutes?

180
00:08:07,954 --> 00:08:10,534
We couldn't have written
some of the stuff the way-- You know?

181
00:08:11,057 --> 00:08:12,727
So we try to replicate
as much as possible...

182
00:08:13,126 --> 00:08:14,876
.. the conditions
on the recording stage.

183
00:08:15,295 --> 00:08:17,345
So the actors could even get out
from behind the podium...

184
00:08:17,797 --> 00:08:19,107
..and move around
and act things out.

185
00:08:19,466 --> 00:08:24,686
And we had a guy with a boom,
following them on occasion.

186
00:08:25,972 --> 00:08:28,142
And I just freed them up
to get more physical with everything...

187
00:08:28,608 --> 00:08:29,658
..and make it real.

188
00:08:29,976 --> 00:08:34,076
l remember many times, you guys
would pick up a video camera.

189
00:08:34,813 --> 00:08:38,414
And really be in-- Quite intrusive
with the camera like you were there.

190
00:08:39,085 --> 00:08:41,225
That's right. We did that to Jeff.
That's right.

191
00:08:41,688 --> 00:08:43,967
And you really did throw
something at us.

192
00:08:44,758 --> 00:08:46,538
How's your head, by the way, there?

193
00:08:48,461 --> 00:08:53,061
Sal Masekela,
the real voice of the X Games.

194
00:08:54,200 --> 00:08:56,160
This all worked--
I forgot how this happened.

195
00:08:57,237 --> 00:08:58,937
But we came up with the idea that...

196
00:08:59,339 --> 00:09:00,739
. if we had
this fake sports network...

197
00:09:01,107 --> 00:09:03,187
..we could just get a lot of information
out in short order.

198
00:09:03,643 --> 00:09:06,983
And then coincidentally,
Sal dropped by the studio...

199
00:09:07,614 --> 00:09:10,394
..through Quicksilver
and was a perfect match.

200
00:09:10,950 --> 00:09:12,620
Over lunch, I think,
we had an accidental lunch--

201
00:09:13,019 --> 00:09:17,029
Yeah, we just talked about it,
how we could use him in the movie.

202
00:09:17,757 --> 00:09:18,776
And same with Kelly.

203
00:09:19,092 --> 00:09:21,401
Yeah, they did their scenes together.
We had Kelly, Rob and--

204
00:09:21,895 --> 00:09:22,975
-Yeah, all three.
-And Sal.

205
00:09:23,296 --> 00:09:25,316
They weren't originally a part of--
Kelly and Rob...

206
00:09:25,765 --> 00:09:28,255
.. weren't originally in the movie.
They were on as consultants.

207
00:09:28,768 --> 00:09:31,638
To help us get the waves right
and the surf culture right.

208
00:09:32,205 --> 00:09:34,925
-Right.
-But it turned out to be really good.

209
00:09:36,776 --> 00:09:38,945
The twisted Tank.

210
00:09:39,546 --> 00:09:40,536
Diedrich.

211
00:09:41,648 --> 00:09:43,898
You never want to get in there
and help them out...

212
00:09:44,484 --> 00:09:46,564
He is the biggest character
in the movie.

213
00:09:47,020 --> 00:09:49,360
A big personality
and the nicest guy.

214
00:09:49,856 --> 00:09:52,076
He's a really great guy to work with.

215
00:09:52,559 --> 00:09:54,459
But Tank, you know, we tried
to just find something...

216
00:09:54,894 --> 00:09:58,404
...a little bit different for him,
so he wasn't the same old villain.

217
00:09:59,065 --> 00:10:01,465
And I think we came up
with something very unique for him.

218
00:10:01,968 --> 00:10:02,867
Yeah.

219
00:10:03,169 --> 00:10:04,629
We always said he was like
a cross between...

220
00:10:05,004 --> 00:10:07,005
..John McEnroe and a forklift truck.

221
00:10:07,006 --> 00:10:07,996
..John McEnroe and a forklift truck.

222
00:10:10,176 --> 00:10:12,396
Mikey Abromowitz played
by Mario Cantone...

223
00:10:12,879 --> 00:10:15,629
.. is anything but the typical surfer.

224
00:10:16,382 --> 00:10:19,722
He's sort of a-- He's sort of a--

225
00:10:20,720 --> 00:10:22,890
We refer to him
as an office gopher...

226
00:10:23,356 --> 00:10:25,406
.. which got very confusing because
he's really a sandpiper.

227
00:10:25,859 --> 00:10:28,289
And he's the kind of guy,
originally, anyway--

228
00:10:28,795 --> 00:10:30,224
We were thinking of
the kind of guy...

229
00:10:30,597 --> 00:10:33,057
..that really didn't wanna get
his feet wet with his boss.

230
00:10:33,566 --> 00:10:34,766
So the sandpiper's interesting...

231
00:10:35,101 --> 00:10:38,001
.. because they never really seem
to get their feet wet...

232
00:10:38,571 --> 00:10:40,121
.. when they're fishing for....

233
00:10:40,673 --> 00:10:42,783
Yup, and he's a talent scout
that doesn't surf.

234
00:10:44,043 --> 00:10:46,503
A surfing talent scout.

235
00:10:49,149 --> 00:10:52,339
But Mario gave him a great edge.

236
00:10:52,952 --> 00:10:57,492
This guy has done this way too much.
Nothing fazes him.

237
00:10:59,926 --> 00:11:03,176
Ash, you brought up Mario
from a one-man show.

238
00:11:03,796 --> 00:11:06,606
Oh, yeah, my wife and I saw him
in his last show in Broadway.

239
00:11:07,167 --> 00:11:09,357
His one-man comedy show.

240
00:11:09,836 --> 00:11:11,826
And a few months later,
we're trying to figure out...

241
00:11:12,272 --> 00:11:14,962
..who would do the voice
and popped in the head.

242
00:11:15,775 --> 00:11:17,295
-Great.
-He's a huge animation fan.

243
00:11:17,677 --> 00:11:19,847
He knew more about animation
than we did.

244
00:11:20,880 --> 00:11:24,250
Jon Heder knows about animation.
Jon Heder, Chicken Joe.

245
00:11:27,220 --> 00:11:29,330
Now, this was added late.

246
00:11:29,789 --> 00:11:32,039
But it was about...

247
00:11:32,659 --> 00:11:35,209
.. showing what Cody really wanted,
you know?

248
00:11:35,728 --> 00:11:37,037
It's not about winning
the competition.

249
00:11:37,397 --> 00:11:39,417
He just wants somebody
to be there for him.

250
00:11:39,866 --> 00:11:43,376
And he clearly doesn't have it
in his hometown.

251
00:11:44,037 --> 00:11:45,347
You know, I think it was also added...

252
00:11:45,705 --> 00:11:48,195
..S0 that he would have a chance
with mom.

253
00:11:48,708 --> 00:11:50,137
Because originally,
it wasn't in there...

254
00:11:50,510 --> 00:11:54,140
..$0 he would just go from the fish pile
to the water, to the whale.

255
00:11:54,814 --> 00:11:57,064
-He's gone. He never says goodbye.
