256
00:11:57,550 --> 00:11:58,479
To his family.

257
00:11:58,785 --> 00:12:00,625
And this was his chance
to say goodbye...

258
00:12:01,054 --> 00:12:03,574
..but mom, still,
is not really interested, so....

259
00:12:04,090 --> 00:12:05,840
It seemed to help his character
a little bit better.

260
00:12:06,259 --> 00:12:08,560
Well, I think it re-injects that pathos
that you have for this young kid...

261
00:12:08,561 --> 00:12:10,111
Well, I think it re-injects that pathos
that you have for this young kid...

262
00:12:10,496 --> 00:12:13,045
.. that just has a passion
right from the beginning.

263
00:12:13,566 --> 00:12:15,346
Lets you know what he really wants,
what's important.

264
00:12:15,768 --> 00:12:17,958
-And how no one understands him.
-Yeah.

265
00:12:21,874 --> 00:12:25,354
I gotta thank my wife, Nicole,
for that toucan line.

266
00:12:26,112 --> 00:12:29,072
She had a handle on who Mike was.

267
00:12:33,519 --> 00:12:35,709
Can't this blubber ball go any faster?
Step on it, fish sticks!

268
00:12:36,956 --> 00:12:38,596
Bunch of other surfers up there
on the whale.

269
00:12:38,992 --> 00:12:42,332
They were gonna be bigger characters
initially. We have an Aussie up there.

270
00:12:42,962 --> 00:12:45,182
Japanese surfer.

271
00:12:46,299 --> 00:12:48,409
-Brazilian.
-Brazilian, yeah.

272
00:12:49,035 --> 00:12:51,084
There's so much material
that you discover...

273
00:12:51,537 --> 00:12:52,877
.. when you create a movie like this.

274
00:12:53,239 --> 00:12:56,199
Particularly, I think, as a documentary
or reality show.

275
00:12:56,776 --> 00:12:58,205
You can really get
into these characters.

276
00:12:58,578 --> 00:12:59,948
And then, at the end of the day...

277
00:13:00,313 --> 00:13:02,453
.. you realize, well, you got 80 minutes
and a story to tell.

278
00:13:02,915 --> 00:13:08,454
So there were a lot of casualties
simply from the point of view...

279
00:13:09,756 --> 00:13:13,236
..of not having enough time
to get into all those back-stories.

280
00:13:13,893 --> 00:13:16,473
-Casualties.
-Casualties.

281
00:13:17,096 --> 00:13:18,646
It sounds painful.

282
00:13:19,032 --> 00:13:20,732
The whole idea of Cody
chasing this whale...

283
00:13:21,134 --> 00:13:24,384
..Was inspired by surfers...

284
00:13:25,004 --> 00:13:28,284
...who ride the wakes of oil tankers,
I think, in the Gulf of Mexico.

285
00:13:28,908 --> 00:13:29,778
-Yeah.
-Yeah.

286
00:13:30,076 --> 00:13:31,036
Yup.

287
00:13:32,312 --> 00:13:34,392
They had a hard time getting
these two together too.

288
00:13:34,847 --> 00:13:37,807
We had to get Joe and Cody
get an introduction...

289
00:13:38,384 --> 00:13:41,514
.. before we get to the next sequence
of Pen Gu where the just takes off, so...

290
00:13:42,121 --> 00:13:45,281
Yeah, they needed a quick moment
to bond.

291
00:13:45,892 --> 00:13:47,292
Deeply enough that you could buy...

292
00:13:47,660 --> 00:13:49,560
.. that Joe would spend
the next several days...

293
00:13:49,996 --> 00:13:51,836
..going to find Cody
as he's lost in the jungle.

294
00:13:52,999 --> 00:13:54,899
Joe, kind of--
We always had that character.

295
00:13:55,335 --> 00:13:58,795
He was gonna be that guy that,
you know, nothing fazed him.

296
00:13:59,439 --> 00:14:01,608
But we did have. We went down
the road where he got a little.

297
00:14:02,075 --> 00:14:04,245
You know, he'd get angry sometimes
or this or that...

298
00:14:04,711 --> 00:14:07,171
..and you realize, this guy just--
Nothing fazes Joe.

299
00:14:07,680 --> 00:14:08,609
Everything is good.

300
00:14:08,915 --> 00:14:09,875
Every moment is good.

301
00:14:10,183 --> 00:14:12,992
And he turned out to be one
of the favorite characters in the movie.

302
00:14:13,553 --> 00:14:18,123
He seems to epitomize
a quintessential surfer attitude.

303
00:14:20,693 --> 00:14:21,893
Inspired Ash Brannon moment
there.

304
00:14:23,529 --> 00:14:24,899
Butt freeze?

305
00:14:25,264 --> 00:14:28,894
No, the whole whale spout.
Joe being blasted off in the air.

306
00:14:29,569 --> 00:14:32,029
Finding a way to end that scene
properly.

307
00:14:33,172 --> 00:14:35,782
Our visual development team,
Paul Lasaine...

308
00:14:36,709 --> 00:14:38,409
..Marcelo Vignali.

309
00:14:39,712 --> 00:14:41,322
Hope I pronounced it right.

310
00:14:41,714 --> 00:14:43,524
Armand Serrano, Ron Lukas...

311
00:14:44,650 --> 00:14:46,050
..designed a beautiful world.

312
00:14:48,054 --> 00:14:49,544
-The characters.
-They're natural primitive.

313
00:14:49,922 --> 00:14:52,412
-Oh, yes, Sylvain Deboissy.
-Sylvain Deboissy.

314
00:14:54,060 --> 00:14:54,989
He had a real challenge...

315
00:14:55,294 --> 00:14:57,754
.. because most of our characters
.
are penguins.

316
00:14:58,398 --> 00:15:00,448
It's real easy for them to start
looking alike...

317
00:15:00,900 --> 00:15:02,160
..but he gave them all distinction.

318
00:15:03,469 --> 00:15:06,129
They ended up having different tattoos
to help you....

319
00:15:07,140 --> 00:15:10,540
I think it started with
the Hawaiian shirt thing.

320
00:15:11,177 --> 00:15:14,427
-That was a Marcelo invention, right?
-Yeah, Marcelo.

321
00:15:15,314 --> 00:15:16,834
It was a brilliant, brilliant invention...

322
00:15:17,216 --> 00:15:20,676
.. because it just carried forward
to everybody else then.

323
00:15:22,288 --> 00:15:24,508
I think we wanted to find
a much more organic way...

324
00:15:24,991 --> 00:15:28,831
..to actually feel the excitement
of this island and the MTV style.

325
00:15:30,730 --> 00:15:33,250
You know, music video
was the best way to go.

326
00:15:33,766 --> 00:15:35,106
Introduced a lot of things in here.

327
00:15:35,468 --> 00:15:38,367
Introduced the fact that Joe and Cody
are really good friends.

328
00:15:39,939 --> 00:15:41,339
Or have become really good friends.

329
00:15:41,707 --> 00:15:45,047
Yeah, saving--
Joe saving Cody made all that work.

330
00:15:45,678 --> 00:15:47,578
Just instant bond, you get that.

331
00:15:48,014 --> 00:15:51,294
Like when we pulled you out
from in front of that moving train.

332
00:15:52,285 --> 00:15:54,214
Yeah, the one that you were driving.

333
00:15:54,654 --> 00:15:57,144
Coming through! Oh, crap.

334
00:15:57,657 --> 00:16:00,557
-Introduction of Lani.
-Lani.

335
00:16:01,127 --> 00:16:04,026
Now, the squid life preserver.

336
00:16:04,597 --> 00:16:09,727
That was an invention of our character
designer, Sylvan Deboissy.

337
00:16:11,304 --> 00:16:13,324
Brilliant invention.

338
00:16:13,773 --> 00:16:18,053
This is why animation is great
because of that squid.

339
00:16:20,213 --> 00:16:23,173
This is also a scene that Zooey
ad-libbed.

340
00:16:23,850 --> 00:16:26,160
She came up
with the character Arnold.

341
00:16:27,453 --> 00:16:29,882
She was holding a sandbag,
remember?

342
00:16:30,389 --> 00:16:32,849
-And invented that character.
-That's right.

343
00:16:33,359 --> 00:16:35,439
Then we said, "Well, she's talking
to a kid, we need a kid."

344
00:16:35,895 --> 00:16:37,005
And Chris Buck...

345
00:16:37,997 --> 00:16:40,337
.. took a portable DAT recorder
home.

346
00:16:40,833 --> 00:16:42,323
-Yup.
-And just recorded his--

347
00:16:42,702 --> 00:16:44,192
What was he, eight at that time
or seven?

348
00:16:44,570 --> 00:16:47,200
-He was probably eight.
-His son, Reed, just at home.

349
00:16:47,740 --> 00:16:49,230
To do scratch
and it turned out so good...

350
00:16:49,609 --> 00:16:50,809
..we had to use it in the production.

351
00:16:51,143 --> 00:16:53,453
Yeah, because a lot of times
there's nothing worse than an adult...

352
00:16:53,946 --> 00:16:56,696
..trying to do a kid voice.

353
00:16:58,284 --> 00:17:00,214
So we have real kids.

354
00:17:00,786 --> 00:17:02,626
l love my job.
I have an amazing job.

355
00:17:03,923 --> 00:17:06,413
This is so Zooey.
This whole thing here.

356
00:17:06,925 --> 00:17:10,056
Again, the camera work here,
working so beautifully.

357
00:17:10,663 --> 00:17:11,532
They're gonna go...

358
00:17:11,830 --> 00:17:13,971
..for the interesting thing
that's happening at the moment.

359
00:17:14,433 --> 00:17:16,953
That would be this little kid
who's about to drown.

360
00:17:19,438 --> 00:17:21,368
And James Williams,
our head of layout.

361
00:17:22,775 --> 00:17:25,435
Wonderful cinematography
in this movie.

362
00:17:27,680 --> 00:17:29,990
A lot of times, the camera--

363
00:17:30,483 --> 00:17:33,113
We had to sort of give the illusion
that the camera was finding the action.

364
00:17:33,653 --> 00:17:34,793
It couldn't be ahead of it.

365
00:17:35,121 --> 00:17:37,871
As you would normally create
these shots at this stage.

366
00:17:38,424 --> 00:17:41,414
-Remember?
-No, no. Not really.

367
00:17:43,029 --> 00:17:46,629
More of the archival footage that we--
Little scratches on the side.

368
00:17:47,300 --> 00:17:50,260
Actually, that stuff is pretty easy to do
from what I've been told.

369
00:17:50,937 --> 00:17:52,306
It looks hard.

370
00:17:52,672 --> 00:17:54,192
I think a lot of times it was just--

371
00:17:54,574 --> 00:17:56,384
Well, you know,
the guys would do the work...

372
00:17:56,809 --> 00:17:58,979
..and it'd be beautiful and pristine
and the color would be perfect.

373
00:17:59,445 --> 00:18:01,085
And then, we would say,
"Okay, now, make it look--"

374
00:18:01,480 --> 00:18:04,030
Yeah, muck it up,
make it look pretty bad.

375
00:18:04,550 --> 00:18:06,330
And then, you know--

376
00:18:07,987 --> 00:18:10,037
-They would do it.
-And then, on the long run, they go:

377
00:18:10,489 --> 00:18:12,329
"Okay, I get it.
I know what you guys are doing."

378
00:18:14,427 --> 00:18:16,417
It was all part of getting
a real organic look...

379
00:18:17,630 --> 00:18:19,820
..and feel for the movie.
That was really important to us.

380
00:18:20,299 --> 00:18:21,349
That it didn't feel CG.

381
00:18:22,335 --> 00:18:23,795
And in fact...

382
00:18:24,537 --> 00:18:25,527
.. archival footage aside...

383
00:18:25,838 --> 00:18:28,828
..every shot including shots like this
have film grain.

384
00:18:29,408 --> 00:18:31,108
Because when we saw
the original images...

385
00:18:31,510 --> 00:18:32,590
.. they were too perfect.

386
00:18:32,912 --> 00:18:34,842
And, too, almost a little sterile.

387
00:18:35,281 --> 00:18:39,061
But adding that little bit of film grain
took the edge off everything.

388
00:18:40,019 --> 00:18:42,679
The character of Tank
was really articulated...

389
00:18:44,690 --> 00:18:46,440
.. by Jeff Ranjo, our head of story.

390
00:18:46,859 --> 00:18:51,279
He took what could have been
a real cutout, cardboard-like villain...

391
00:18:52,898 --> 00:18:55,477
..and went somewhere different
with him as you'll see later.

392
00:18:57,203 --> 00:18:58,753
We used to have a sequence...

393
00:18:59,138 --> 00:19:01,858
.. that took us off into a big luau party
right here.

394
00:19:02,408 --> 00:19:05,247
And actually, Cody was gonna ride
the wave the next day, isn't that right?

395
00:19:05,811 --> 00:19:06,711
It slowed everything down.

396
00:19:07,013 --> 00:19:08,793
We had, like, a three-hour first act,
didn't we?

397
00:19:09,215 --> 00:19:12,254
Yeah, 80 minutes. Get to the point.

398
00:19:13,419 --> 00:19:15,169
This used to be
a much more complicated scene.

399
00:19:15,588 --> 00:19:17,197
It was a big dialogue-driven--

400
00:19:17,590 --> 00:19:18,730
Or even before that, remember?

401
00:19:19,058 --> 00:19:22,128
When Cody was saving Chicken Joe
from being beaten up.

402
00:19:22,728 --> 00:19:24,838
-That's right.
-And then the Ransoms came in.

403
00:19:25,297 --> 00:19:27,957
They were Tank's cronies.
And they held Cody down.

404
00:19:29,335 --> 00:19:32,645
Lani rushed in and flipped Tank
on his back.

405
00:19:33,272 --> 00:19:35,141
That was the three-hour version,
I think.

406
00:19:35,574 --> 00:19:36,884
It was our head of story, Jeff Ranjo.

407
00:19:37,243 --> 00:19:39,822
He came up with the great,
efficient way of just moving forward.

408
00:19:40,346 --> 00:19:40,412
You have the memorial surfboard
out on the rock.

409
00:19:40,413 --> 00:19:42,023
You have the memorial surfboard
out on the rock.

410
00:19:42,415 --> 00:19:44,375
And somebody's throwing rocks at it.

411
00:19:45,618 --> 00:19:48,138
Now, those urchins, they come back
a little bit later.

412
00:19:48,654 --> 00:19:50,434
At least one of them does.

413
00:19:52,058 --> 00:19:54,518
This one used to be, like,
so much longer too.

414
00:19:55,027 --> 00:19:56,397
Cody would--
He wouldn't take a wave.

415
00:19:56,762 --> 00:20:00,131
And he was really-- Really was
wearing his fear on his sleeve.

416
00:20:00,766 --> 00:20:03,456
You just wanted him to wipeout.

417
00:20:04,437 --> 00:20:05,546
l remember nearly doing this.

418
00:20:05,871 --> 00:20:07,541
Of course the wave that I was on
doing that...

419
00:20:08,541 --> 00:20:11,061
..Was about a foot and a half high,
but it was still pretty frightening.

420
00:20:11,577 --> 00:20:13,977
Well, we've had some
of the best teachers in the world.

421
00:20:14,480 --> 00:20:17,110
We had Kelly and Rob
teaching us too, so....

422
00:20:17,650 --> 00:20:19,020
And we still surf the way we do.

423
00:20:19,385 --> 00:20:21,525
-Yup, no reflection on their skill.
-Yup.

424
00:20:21,987 --> 00:20:24,677
-We're still useless.
-l wouldn't call it surfing.

425
00:20:26,892 --> 00:20:29,322
Now, we can't tell you anything
about the waves technically...

426
00:20:29,829 --> 00:20:31,579
.. because we don't know anything
about the waves.

427
00:20:31,997 --> 00:20:35,657
And we all, between us, we have
a brain the size of a hamster.

428
00:20:38,037 --> 00:20:40,617
But a lot of the scenes with the water,
and the jungles and everything...

429
00:20:41,140 --> 00:20:43,510
..1 know we would look at them
and say, "Fantastic."

430
00:20:44,009 --> 00:20:46,999
And the guys would say,
"Yeah, but we're not done yet."

431
00:20:47,947 --> 00:20:50,496
You know, and a few days later,
it would look even better.

432
00:20:51,016 --> 00:20:53,566
And these guys
kept topping themselves.

433
00:20:54,653 --> 00:20:57,493
And this one, this is an odd one
where we kept trying, you know...

434
00:20:58,057 --> 00:21:00,867
...well, would it be
just two wipeouts, three?

435
00:21:01,427 --> 00:21:03,006
Rule of comedy is three.

436
00:21:03,395 --> 00:21:05,035
But somehow when we added
the fourth one in...

437
00:21:05,431 --> 00:21:07,181
.. people really laughed.
The three was funny.

438
00:21:07,800 --> 00:21:10,550
The fourth one they weren't expecting,
especially the different angle.

439
00:21:11,103 --> 00:21:13,213
Plus Cody had said, "You know,
you're gonna wanna watch it...

440
00:21:13,672 --> 00:21:16,282
..one, two, three.
Over and over and over and over."

441
00:21:17,810 --> 00:21:20,470
Now, why the camera people
didn't go and rescue Cody--

442
00:21:21,013 --> 00:21:23,033
-I'm not sure why they--
-There's a rule of noninvolvement.

443
00:21:23,482 --> 00:21:25,562
-Oh, right. That's right.
-Yeah, don't make the news.

444
00:21:26,018 --> 00:21:28,038
-Just report the news.
-Yeah.

445
00:21:29,455 --> 00:21:31,504
We used to have Lani out there,
doing the rescue.

446
00:21:31,957 --> 00:21:32,917
Cody was passed out...

447
00:21:33,225 --> 00:21:35,155
..and she was the one
kind of suffering for Cody.

448
00:21:35,594 --> 00:21:37,294
I don't know why we did that.

449
00:21:37,696 --> 00:21:39,396
-Now, this scene...
-Try, you try.

450
00:21:39,799 --> 00:21:42,869
..described to us by a guy
from Quicksilver and he walked in.

451
00:21:43,469 --> 00:21:44,339
Yeah.

452
00:21:44,637 --> 00:21:47,476
He described what it's like
to almost drown.

453
00:21:48,040 --> 00:21:49,210
It stayed with this, because I think...

454
00:21:49,542 --> 00:21:51,562
. it was early on that he showed us
that-- You know...

455
00:21:52,011 --> 00:21:54,731
..what it looked like to drown
as he's, sort of, like, lying on the floor...

456
00:21:55,281 --> 00:21:57,591
..of the conference room
with his arms and legs in the air.

457
00:21:58,083 --> 00:21:59,013
-l forgot about that.
-Yeah.

458
00:21:59,318 --> 00:22:00,988
A lot of the surfers talk about
how once you're--

459
00:22:01,387 --> 00:22:02,907
If you've wiped out
and you're under water...

460
00:22:03,289 --> 00:22:05,979
.. often, you can't tell which way is up,
which way is down.

461
00:22:06,525 --> 00:22:08,335
And you'll be swimming thinking
you're surfacing...

462
00:22:08,761 --> 00:22:10,221
..and you'll hit the bottom
of the reef...

463
00:22:10,596 --> 00:22:11,996
.. realize you're going
the wrong way.

464
00:22:12,364 --> 00:22:14,204
When you come up for air,
sometimes that next wave...

465
00:22:14,633 --> 00:22:18,113
.18 right down on top of you.
You don't even get another breath.

466
00:22:18,771 --> 00:22:20,911
-Tank, you okay?
-Tank needs fuel.

467
00:22:21,373 --> 00:22:23,683
Now, he says it tastes like--

468
00:22:24,510 --> 00:22:25,379
-Shellfish.
-Shellfish.

469
00:22:25,678 --> 00:22:27,198
Shellfish, I just wanna be clear
about that.

