Cody puts it together.

709
00:34:25,830 --> 00:34:28,020
It's a very organic reveal that--

710
00:34:28,500 --> 00:34:31,520
l remember we had so many ideas
about Z having a scar...

711
00:34:35,239 --> 00:34:36,549
..a Cupboard of trophies....

712
00:34:36,908 --> 00:34:39,777
Well, the question was always, like,
"How would Cody know who this--?"

713
00:34:40,344 --> 00:34:41,804
It's like,
"Wait a minute, Cody's not--"

714
00:34:42,714 --> 00:34:45,054
He's pretty bright.
He's gonna put it together, you know.

715
00:34:45,550 --> 00:34:48,300
You see this character reacting
the way they do.

716
00:34:48,987 --> 00:34:51,177
Often in story development,
you work on these things.

717
00:34:51,656 --> 00:34:53,056
And you second guess yourself.

718
00:34:53,425 --> 00:34:55,615
Or you're being guessed
by a lot of people around you.

719
00:34:56,094 --> 00:34:59,084
All for good reasons, really,
but you kind of forget...

720
00:34:59,664 --> 00:35:01,774
.. that people are discovering
their journey with you.

721
00:35:02,233 --> 00:35:07,453
And sometimes you try too hard
to disguise things without realizing...

722
00:35:08,340 --> 00:35:10,450
.. that your perspective as a storyteller
is everything.

723
00:35:10,909 --> 00:35:12,219
You know the story inside out.

724
00:35:12,577 --> 00:35:14,387
But the audience
is just walking this path...

725
00:35:14,813 --> 00:35:16,773
..and discovering things
as they come up.

726
00:35:17,215 --> 00:35:20,405
-What happened?
-l don't want to talk about it.

727
00:35:21,019 --> 00:35:23,388
I love the way he looks
in the camera there.

728
00:35:27,258 --> 00:35:29,747
We were always trying to keep
that idea alive...

729
00:35:30,261 --> 00:35:34,181
.. that these characters
were going about their business.

730
00:35:34,899 --> 00:35:36,569
But at times,
when they were revealing things...

731
00:35:36,968 --> 00:35:38,957
.. they didn't wanna be revealed,
in particularly with Z...

732
00:35:39,404 --> 00:35:41,104
.. they'd looked right at the camera.

733
00:35:41,940 --> 00:35:44,840
Yeah, we wanted awareness
of the camera throughout.

734
00:35:45,510 --> 00:35:48,060
Not too often,
but enough to remind you...

735
00:35:48,580 --> 00:35:50,009
.. that there's cameras
on the beach.

736
00:35:50,382 --> 00:35:52,752
And there's only 800
and something shots in the movie.

737
00:35:53,251 --> 00:35:56,121
It's a really low shot count
for a movie like this.

738
00:35:56,688 --> 00:35:58,358
Especially when we get to
making the board...

739
00:35:58,757 --> 00:36:01,977
..which is very long.
Couple of long scenes.

740
00:36:02,594 --> 00:36:04,024
We wanted the limitation
of the camera...

741
00:36:04,396 --> 00:36:05,886
.. having to stay away
from the characters.

742
00:36:06,264 --> 00:36:09,484
It couldn't get exactly where it wanted
to get for the perfect shot every time.

743
00:36:12,437 --> 00:36:16,217
We had this kid thing all as one
and then, I think, lvan our editor...

744
00:36:17,542 --> 00:36:18,912
. Split it up into three.

745
00:36:19,277 --> 00:36:22,317
Just kind of wrap the whole thing
around, yeah.

746
00:36:22,914 --> 00:36:24,664
lvan's not only a fantastic editor...

747
00:36:25,083 --> 00:36:29,363
. he's a really great,
accomplished surfer himself.

748
00:36:30,121 --> 00:36:33,811
It turned out to be indispensable
that he was--

749
00:36:34,492 --> 00:36:36,302
Could help us connect
to the surf world...

750
00:36:36,728 --> 00:36:39,388
..and keep it real every day.

751
00:36:40,732 --> 00:36:43,572
Jack Ranjo's big line coming up.

752
00:36:44,135 --> 00:36:46,095
He's a dirty trashcan full of poop.

753
00:36:46,938 --> 00:36:48,688
Hey, now, nobody made him
say that line, Chris.

754
00:36:49,107 --> 00:36:50,397
That was his own line.

755
00:36:50,742 --> 00:36:52,962
Yeah, well, maybe Jeff wrote it.
We don't know.

756
00:36:53,812 --> 00:36:55,712
-Hey, what's that?
-And Tank's mom--

757
00:36:57,115 --> 00:36:59,165
-What a looker.
-Oh, yeah.

758
00:36:59,718 --> 00:37:01,998
-Played by Diedrich Bader.
-Yeah.

759
00:37:02,587 --> 00:37:05,167
Who is also a looker
as a matter of fact.

760
00:37:07,926 --> 00:37:10,356
Okay, this is probably the weirdest
sequence in the whole movie.

761
00:37:10,862 --> 00:37:11,852
Yeah, we admit it.

762
00:37:12,163 --> 00:37:15,093
-And it's Jeff Ranjo's fault.
-Jeff Ranjo, it's all his fault.

763
00:37:15,667 --> 00:37:19,386
Then Diedrich ran with it
and we encouraged it and all that.

764
00:37:20,638 --> 00:37:23,098
But as strange as this is, you know,
we were questioning it...

765
00:37:23,608 --> 00:37:25,338
..-you know,
is this just too out there?

766
00:37:25,744 --> 00:37:28,524
Then I think about at the same time,
it was Super Bowl Sunday...

767
00:37:29,914 --> 00:37:33,574
..and in this particular Super Bowl,
they had--

768
00:37:34,252 --> 00:37:35,922
When you cut away
from the game...

769
00:37:36,821 --> 00:37:38,841
.. they would cut to photographs
of the players...

770
00:37:39,290 --> 00:37:40,580
.. posing with the trophy...

771
00:37:40,925 --> 00:37:43,145
..and kissing the trophy
and hugging the trophy.

772
00:37:43,628 --> 00:37:45,998
And we realize this is not so...

773
00:37:47,132 --> 00:37:48,682
-... far out.
-This isn't weird.

774
00:37:49,067 --> 00:37:50,997
You know, but we pushed it.

775
00:37:51,870 --> 00:37:53,540
We make a little weirder.

776
00:37:54,072 --> 00:37:56,472
We had a test screening
and this first version...

777
00:37:56,975 --> 00:37:58,755
.. Slightly, sort of the same,
people didn't like.

778
00:37:59,177 --> 00:38:02,277
We did a different version, edited it.
Nobody liked.

779
00:38:02,881 --> 00:38:05,221
So we went back
to the original version.

780
00:38:06,151 --> 00:38:07,231
-You know...
-l like the pretty--

781
00:38:07,552 --> 00:38:08,422
Kids get it on one level.

782
00:38:08,720 --> 00:38:10,529
Adults get it on another.

783
00:38:11,389 --> 00:38:12,879
Well, one of the ideas
is that Cody was--

784
00:38:13,258 --> 00:38:14,457
That's all Cody wanted to do,
was to win the trophy.

785
00:38:14,459 --> 00:38:15,658
That's all Cody wanted to do,
was to win the trophy.

786
00:38:15,994 --> 00:38:18,774
Epitomized winning. Well, we thought,
"What if our villain--?

787
00:38:19,330 --> 00:38:21,230
That's what he's all about.

788
00:38:21,666 --> 00:38:23,746
It's all about the trophy."

789
00:38:24,803 --> 00:38:27,792
One of our best
documentary shots here.

790
00:38:28,373 --> 00:38:31,303
Camera follows. It's still one shot.

791
00:38:33,945 --> 00:38:35,555
Hey, who said you--

792
00:38:35,947 --> 00:38:38,287
Turn the board around.
Get back here.

793
00:38:39,117 --> 00:38:40,697
I think the water is--

794
00:38:41,085 --> 00:38:43,045
Some of the best water
is when it's like that.

795
00:38:43,488 --> 00:38:45,328
Not necessarily
when there's breaking waves.

796
00:38:45,757 --> 00:38:46,717
I just love this scene.

797
00:38:47,025 --> 00:38:49,655
-You wanna jump in.
-Yeah.

798
00:38:50,195 --> 00:38:52,535
-Well, I'd like you to jump in there.
-Beautiful.

799
00:38:53,031 --> 00:38:54,111
Jump off.

800
00:38:56,668 --> 00:38:59,538
We never got tired of putting Cody
through the ringer.

801
00:39:00,104 --> 00:39:02,274
He needed to be.

802
00:39:02,740 --> 00:39:03,669
Well, it's a cocky--

803
00:39:03,975 --> 00:39:06,964
A cocky character,
you don't mind seeing him....

804
00:39:07,545 --> 00:39:09,005
That was the interesting thing
with him...

805
00:39:09,380 --> 00:39:12,690
.. was keeping him sort of driven
and cocky and that--

806
00:39:13,318 --> 00:39:15,098
-Likable?
-Likable.

807
00:39:15,520 --> 00:39:18,100
-Gotta keep him likable.
-And believable, I guess.

808
00:39:19,591 --> 00:39:21,020
-Mychael Danna's score.
-Oh, yeah.

809
00:39:21,392 --> 00:39:23,792
-We gotta--
-Funny little ditty that he did here.

810
00:39:24,295 --> 00:39:26,405
The guy was versatile
more than like--

811
00:39:26,865 --> 00:39:28,035
-That's--
-He's amazing, amazing.

812
00:39:28,366 --> 00:39:33,086
But he also wrote the SPEN theme,
the original, the opening theme.

813
00:39:34,873 --> 00:39:36,303
And then the Boneyards.

814
00:39:36,674 --> 00:39:39,694
-Incredible music at the end.
-Score.

815
00:39:41,646 --> 00:39:44,016
Now, this X started off as a gag.

816
00:39:44,515 --> 00:39:45,444
And it also showed...

817
00:39:45,750 --> 00:39:47,740
.. you know, that Zeke was really
connected to the water.

818
00:39:48,186 --> 00:39:49,586
He knew when the waves
were gonna break.

819
00:39:49,954 --> 00:39:52,884
And it was kind of a one-off gag
at one point.

820
00:39:53,458 --> 00:39:55,358
And we'd realize
we could use it later on.

821
00:39:55,793 --> 00:39:57,723
Now, the precursor of that
Was a scene...

822
00:39:58,162 --> 00:39:59,861
...that, [ think, Ed Gombert
had created.

823
00:40:00,265 --> 00:40:01,285
A lovely scene.

824
00:40:01,599 --> 00:40:03,849
Where Z was very much--
Kind of like...

825
00:40:04,335 --> 00:40:06,295
.. he's doing transcendental meditation
on the beach.

826
00:40:06,738 --> 00:40:07,607
Oh, right.

827
00:40:07,906 --> 00:40:09,686
And he was counting down
the waves...

828
00:40:10,108 --> 00:40:12,858
..and he knew exactly
when each wave would break.

829
00:40:13,411 --> 00:40:15,691
With his eyes closed.
He didn't really need it.

830
00:40:16,180 --> 00:40:19,020
That wasn't ultimately, what,
Cody needed to learn.

831
00:40:19,584 --> 00:40:22,134
He didn't have to learn the technique
or the technical aspects of surfing.

832
00:40:22,654 --> 00:40:24,434
He needed to learn
how to have fun.

833
00:40:24,856 --> 00:40:26,816
We could have gone conventional
and said:

834
00:40:27,258 --> 00:40:29,098
"Well, there's gonna be a big contest
in act three...

835
00:40:29,527 --> 00:40:31,427
..and we need to have Cody,
like, training every day...

836
00:40:31,863 --> 00:40:33,062
..in leading up to that.

837
00:40:33,398 --> 00:40:34,508
We tried some versions.

838
00:40:34,832 --> 00:40:36,062
Yeah, they just never--

839
00:40:36,401 --> 00:40:39,711
It wasn't fun and it felt
like you had seen it before.

840
00:40:41,372 --> 00:40:42,982
Now, Rob has hair kind of like that.

841
00:40:43,374 --> 00:40:44,274
And by coincidence...

842
00:40:44,575 --> 00:40:47,535
.. adolescent penguins grow
this crazy, brown feathery stuff...

843
00:40:48,112 --> 00:40:49,692
..out of their head
when they're teenagers.

844
00:40:50,081 --> 00:40:55,271
Not quite as much of a Chia Pet
as Rob became in this movie.

845
00:40:56,254 --> 00:40:58,094
Okay, you gotta tell
our wonderful listeners...

846
00:40:58,523 --> 00:41:00,163
.. about this one right here.

847
00:41:00,558 --> 00:41:02,048
Well, Reed was talking about--

848
00:41:02,427 --> 00:41:04,477
Actually, he loves, you know,
toy guns and stuff like that.

849
00:41:04,929 --> 00:41:06,799
So l was asking him,
"What would you like on your gun?"

850
00:41:07,231 --> 00:41:08,401
He said,
"I'd like grenade launcher."

851
00:41:08,733 --> 00:41:12,213
So we took that out of context
and put it into the surfboard thing.

852
00:41:12,870 --> 00:41:13,799
Those happy accidents.

853
00:41:14,105 --> 00:41:17,415
-Oh, the Pen Guans.
-It's another happy accident.

854
00:41:18,343 --> 00:41:19,863
How many cameramen did we lose
in the movie?

855
00:41:22,780 --> 00:41:26,120
Now, we gotta give a nod
to Jason Lethcoe.

856
00:41:26,751 --> 00:41:28,621
-Yes.
-He really--

857
00:41:29,053 --> 00:41:30,423
Early on in production...

858
00:41:30,788 --> 00:41:32,338
..he took the whole middle
of the movie...

859
00:41:32,724 --> 00:41:33,954
..with Cody and Z...

860
00:41:34,292 --> 00:41:37,042
..and worked out a through line
about making a board.

861
00:41:37,595 --> 00:41:40,435
Now, he-- I think he told us
he was inspired by--

862
00:41:41,265 --> 00:41:42,694
Being in the workshop...

863
00:41:43,067 --> 00:41:45,407
.. With his granddad
when he was a kid.

864
00:41:45,903 --> 00:41:49,803
And he tapped into something here
that's universal.

865
00:41:50,942 --> 00:41:52,672
He really understood
the father-and-son dynamic...

866
00:41:53,077 --> 00:41:54,777
..of these guys.

867
00:41:56,214 --> 00:41:59,524
And in creating this scene,
it had echoes back...

868
00:42:00,151 --> 00:42:02,991
..and into the end of the movie.

869
00:42:03,554 --> 00:42:07,744
The movie, I think, really sort of
added those elements back in...

870
00:42:08,493 --> 00:42:09,982
..to all aspects.

871
00:42:11,662 --> 00:42:13,912
Again a lot of great improv
from Jeff and Shia.

872
00:42:14,399 --> 00:42:15,979
Yeah, they were
in the room together.

873
00:42:16,367 --> 00:42:18,887
I think it was their first time together,
like the second day.

874
00:42:19,404 --> 00:42:21,074
We did three days in a row.

875
00:42:21,472 --> 00:42:24,602
And they did four takes.
That was all we needed.

876
00:42:25,209 --> 00:42:27,138
-Yeah.
-We wanted the overlaps.

877
00:42:27,578 --> 00:42:28,448
We wanted the improv.

878
00:42:28,746 --> 00:42:30,036
We wanted it to feel natural.

879
00:42:30,381 --> 00:42:32,841
This scene could be so written...

880
00:42:33,451 --> 00:42:37,671
..and really traditionally,
the information in this scene--

881
00:42:38,423 --> 00:42:40,823
It could be over in a few seconds.

882
00:42:41,325 --> 00:42:42,555
But to actually experience...

883
00:42:42,894 --> 00:42:44,564
..this relationship developed
on-screen...

884
00:42:44,962 --> 00:42:46,802
. this is kind of the core
of the movie in a way.

885
00:42:47,231 --> 00:42:48,281
-Yeah.
-It is.

886
00:42:49,200 --> 00:42:53,390
We were asked many times to cut it.
Trim it...

887
00:42:54,472 --> 00:42:55,462
..way back.

888
00:42:55,773 --> 00:42:57,033
We kept saying, "I don't know."

889
00:42:57,375 --> 00:42:59,395
I think the whole gag works...

890
00:42:59,844 --> 00:43:02,864
.. because of the tension that builds up
throughout the sequence.

891
00:43:03,448 --> 00:43:06,228
The subtlety of these performances
is just staggering.

892
00:43:06,784 --> 00:43:08,124
But they were cuing off too, I think...

893
00:43:08,486 --> 00:43:10,006
..of the great performances
they were getting.

894
00:43:10,388 --> 00:43:12,118
The very natural cadence
of the actors.

895
00:43:12,523 --> 00:43:15,103
And those little eccentric...

896
00:43:15,626 --> 00:43:18,526
.. you know, characteristics
that you don't normally get...

897
00:43:19,097 --> 00:43:22,117
... because lines are, in other movies,
so delivered.

898
00:43:23,334 --> 00:43:26,053
Very unusual to have two actors
in the same space...

899
00:43:26,604 --> 00:43:29,214
.. acting out a scene
for an animated movie.

900
00:43:29,740 --> 00:43:32,729
Normally, you would record
one actor at atime...

901
00:43:33,311 --> 00:43:36,971
..and then a great deal of work goes
into trying to forge a connection...

902
00:43:37,648 --> 00:43:39,988
.. between the performances.

903
00:43:40,485 --> 00:43:43,235
And that seemed a little crazy to us,
quite honestly. We thought--

904
00:43:43,788 --> 00:43:47,568
"If you want a natural performance,
put them together in the room."

905
00:43:48,359 --> 00:43:51,839
And everyone was worried about them
overlapping dialogue...

906
00:43:52,497 --> 00:43:55,307
..and how it would limit us
when we got back to editorial.

907
00:43:55,867 --> 00:43:57,647
No, we embraced it.

908
00:43:58,169 --> 00:44:01,239
We embraced to a large degree
the idea of spontaneity...

909
00:44:01,839 --> 00:44:04,389
..and kind of being stuck with
what you get on film...

910
00:44:04,909 --> 00:44:05,839
..or what you get on tape.

911
00:44:06,144 --> 00:44:08,013
That's what documentary filmmakers
have to deal with.

912
00:44:08,446 --> 00:44:12,786
It was important to keep that sense
of spontaneous reality in everything.

913
00:44:14,118 --> 00:44:17,808
The camera moves, then obviously,
the character performances...

914
00:44:18,489 --> 00:44:20,389
..the story events.

915
00:44:20,825 --> 00:44:23,634
We wanted a sense of reality
unfolding in front of you...

916
00:44:24,195 --> 00:44:25,775
.. not these sort of...

917
00:44:26,731 --> 00:44:28,751
..preordained events
being locked down...

918
00:44:29,200 --> 00:44:30,250
..in a kind of a formulaic way.

919
00:44:31,035 --> 00:44:32,325
That can sometimes happen.

920
00:44:32,670 --> 00:44:35,190
We had transcripts
of everything that these guys said...

921
00:44:35,706 --> 00:44:38,666
..S0 we could go in and find just the
right things with our highlighters...

922
00:44:39,243 --> 00:44:41,143
.. and try to cut it all together.

923
00:44:41,579 --> 00:44:44,599
We had hours and hours of tape
to work with.

924
00:44:45,183 --> 00:44:46,913
So that made it a lot easier
with the transcripts.

925
00:44:48,486 --> 00:44:50,446
We have to thank
the blistered fingers...

926
00:44:50,888 --> 00:44:52,877
-...of Jeannine. Yeah.
-Jeannine Marques, yes.

927
00:44:55,326 --> 00:44:57,786
So those voices are really good
on those penguins.

928
00:44:58,296 --> 00:45:00,486
-Who plays those guys?
-Why, that would be us.

929
00:45:00,965 --> 00:45:02,425
Sped up.

930
00:45:02,800 --> 00:45:04,290
Well, l have never--

931
00:45:04,702 --> 00:45:06,572
Oh, it is just us.

932
00:45:08,606 --> 00:45:11,186
Again, you know, like with the kids,
you added more kids...

933
00:45:11,709 --> 00:45:13,408
..as the movie went on,
we added more Pen Guans.

934
00:45:14,445 --> 00:45:17,075
-They're a very popular character.
-Yeah.

935
00:45:17,615 --> 00:45:20,745
And John ad-libbed this scene here.

936
00:45:21,352 --> 00:45:22,281
-We just said, "What--?"
-Yeah.

937
00:45:22,587 --> 00:45:26,247
"How would Chicken Joe
take being put in a pot...

938
00:45:26,924 --> 00:45:28,094
..a boiling pot of water...?"

939
00:45:28,859 --> 00:45:31,199
l love the opening up
the pores and....

940
00:45:37,201 --> 00:45:40,601
This is something that-- l remember
you bringing this idea into work, Chris.

941
00:45:41,239 --> 00:45:44,399
The idea of going non-linear
with this sequence.

942
00:45:46,244 --> 00:45:48,874
Going back and forth, yeah.
Cutting ahead.

943
00:45:49,413 --> 00:45:51,873
We always had that struggle of trying
to keep the documentary alive...

944
00:45:52,383 --> 00:45:55,513
.. because sometimes
it would just become too narrative.

945
00:45:56,120 --> 00:45:58,930
We're trying to tell the story
and we forget that it's a documentary.

